
[1]repulse

   REPULSE, n. repuls'. [L. repulsa, from repello; re and pello, to
   drive.]

   1. A being checked in advancing, or driven back by force. The enemy met
   with a repulse and retreated.

   2. Refusal; denial.

               REPULSE, v.t. repuls'. [L. repulsus, repello.]

   To repel; to beat or drive back as, to repulse an assailant or
   advancing enemy.
